Introduction¶

According to White House Data, the average single-parent family has a budget of about $49,000 a year, which is roughly half the budget of the average married family with children. However, during the pandemic, the financial state of every household, and the economy in general. It's important to keep up with the economical state of the world, but without understanding what things were like it's hard to get a full perspective on the present.

For our project we will be primarily looking at US income data from 1994. Our interest is in seeing if we can predict the factors which contribute to a person's income being above or below 50k per year as these are the people who typically need the most help in the form of financial assistance. We also want to see if we can visualize income inequality in income to see if there are any specific groups of people most in need of financial aid.

What's in the data¶

  • age: The age of an individual, this ranges from 17 to 90.
  • workclass: The class of work to which an individual belongs.
  • fnlwgt: The weight assigned to the combination of features (an estimate of how many people belong to this set of features).
  • education: highest level of education.
  • education-num: number of years the person was in school for.
  • marital-status: category indicating marriage status of a person.
  • occupation: profession of a person.
  • relationship: relation of person to family.
  • race: race of a person.
  • sex: gender of a person.
  • capital-gain: capital gained by a person.
  • capital-loss: capital lost by a person.
  • hours per week (hpw): hours per week that the person works.
  • native-country: origin country of a person.

Looking at our dataset we can see that a majority of our observations are making less than 50k dollars per year, in fact there's no age group where there are more people making $50k. Most of the data points are on the younger side of things as we progressively have less and less data. We don't see people making more than 50k until a bit past 20, and the greatest concentration of people making over 50k is approximately in their early to mid 40s. Until around their mid 30s there is a huge difference between the number below 50k and above 50k which evens out at later ages.

There are a few things which draw attention. We see that the biggest source of employment is through privately owned businesses, noting that this bin excludes ownership positions. This category also seems to have the biggest divide between people earning more or less than 50k. This is expected as a lot of privately owned businesses pay minimum wage. Moving on to government positions we see that as we work our way up the divide between incomes becomes less and less, though so does the number of employees. We see that the distribution of pay is much more fair here. For self employment we see that in non incorporated businesses there is a fairly normal divide between earnings, but for incorporated businesses, we actually see that more people make over 50k per year than under. These people are owners which run their own businesses, so it would make sense that especially with more successful businesses that these people would be able to pay themselves more.

We can see that there are a lot of variables for occupation, which is where we begin struggling with the dimensionality of the data. The issue here as seen in the graph above is that the amount of data is making it hard to visualize and draw conclusions from it. This often happens when there are lots of features, some of which are of similar nature. In order to combat this issue we will be performing some basic dimensionality reduction. We will do this by grouping together certain occupations under a joint banner.

Dealing with categorical variables is not always as easy as here, so it might help to read more about them if you try to work with a model of your own. For the grouping on this model I used: https://www.analyticsvidhya.com/blog/2015/11/easy-methods-deal-categorical-variables-predictive-modeling/, consulting the combine levels section on how to reduce redundancy.

We can see here that there is no occupation which pays more than 50k on average. We can see that blue collar jobs and service jobs have the highest differences between the number of people making above and below 50k. Blue collar jobs cover a lot of occupations, a lot of which can typically be done without higher education, which is consistent with our findings earlier. Both blue collar jobs and service jobs can sometimes be seen using unskilled labor, which further explains the lower pay. Sales jobs also see a fairly big difference as pay can vary wildly depending on the importance of the position and the product which they are selling. Blue collar and professional jobs have probably the most people being paid more than 50k per year. These jobs typically require a high education which again, is consistent with our findings. In addition these jobs typically have salaried employees rather than hourly, which further contributes to the greater quantity of high paying jobs.

Motivation¶

What are we trying to learn here? I think most of us can think of societal factors that contribute to the income gap in our society. We want to learn is what factors contribute to this in our data. Results could aid in figuring out which groups to assist in efforts to balance out these income discrepancies. Personally I wanted to know if factors like race and gender and years of education would impact a persons income. We want to know if the data supports our theories, if not, then what does it actually say, and can we trust these results. If so, can we also visualize these results?

Importance of Features Random Forests¶

We calculated the top 5 most important features in this model. Which is displayed in the bar graph below utilizing, mean decrease in impurity. This calculates each feature importance as the sum over the number of splits that include the feature, proportional to the number of samples it splits. The top 5 most important features, excluding were: age, realationship to family,capital gain, hours worked per week (hpw), and number of years of education.

What surprised us were features such as work class,native country,education race, and gender were so small, so we decided to look at our data a bit more closely. That is why plotted the representation of these features above. All the features besides education did not vary in diversity of values in that feature. In response to such low diversity we want to look at groups with low diversity individually. We will plot the train and test accuracy of those groups.

Plotting Accuracy of Features with Low Diversity Individually¶

Below we created a function 'plotAccuracyforFeature' which takes in the name of the feature in our dataframe and divides the data by the difference in value of that feature. trains the data on each instances and determines the traing accuracy and test accuracy then plots the difference between each unique value in that feature.

In [144]:
def plotAccuracyforFeature(feature):
    feature_dfs = {}
    for feat in original_data[feature].unique():
        feature_dfs[feat] = (original_data.loc[original_data[feature] == feat])
        
    for feat in feature_dfs.keys():
        feature_dfs[feat]['workclass'] = le.fit_transform(feature_dfs[feat]['workclass'])
        feature_dfs[feat]['highest_education'] = le.fit_transform(feature_dfs[feat]['highest_education'])
        feature_dfs[feat]['marital_status'] = le.fit_transform(feature_dfs[feat]['marital_status'])
        feature_dfs[feat]['occupation'] = le.fit_transform(feature_dfs[feat]['occupation'])
        feature_dfs[feat]['relationship'] = le.fit_transform(feature_dfs[feat]['relationship'])
        feature_dfs[feat]['sex'] = le.fit_transform(feature_dfs[feat]['sex'])
        feature_dfs[feat]['race'] = le.fit_transform(feature_dfs[feat]['race'])
        feature_dfs[feat]['native_country'] = le.fit_transform(feature_dfs[feat]['native_country'])
        
        feature_dfs[feat] = feature_dfs[feat].drop(feature, axis=1)
     
    
    accuracy = {}
    for feat in feature_dfs.keys():
        sc = StandardScaler()
        data_x = feature_dfs[feat].drop('salary', axis = 'columns')
        
        y = feature_dfs[feat]['salary']

        scaled_data_x = sc.fit_transform(data_x)
        x = pd.DataFrame(scaled_data_x, columns = data_x.columns)

        
        if x.shape[0] == 1:
            X_train = X_test = x
            y_train =  y_test = y
        else:
            X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
             x, y, test_size=0.20, random_state=42)

        forest = RandomForestClassifier()
        forest = forest.fit(X_train, y_train)
        
        train_pred = forest.predict(X_train)
        test_pred = forest.predict(X_test)
        test_acc = accuracy_score(y_test, test_pred)
        train_acc = accuracy_score(y_train, train_pred)

        accuracy[feat] = {'trainAcc': float(train_acc), 'testAcc': float(test_acc)}
        
    
    feat_accuracy_df = []
    for key in accuracy.keys():
        tmp = [key, accuracy[key]['trainAcc'],accuracy[key]['testAcc']]
        feat_accuracy_df.append(tmp)

    feat_accuracy_df = np.array(feat_accuracy_df)
    feat_accuracy_df = pd.DataFrame(feat_accuracy_df, columns=[feature,'TrainAccuracy','TestAccuracy'])
    feat_accuracy_df['TrainAccuracy'] = feat_accuracy_df['TrainAccuracy'].astype(float)
    feat_accuracy_df['TestAccuracy'] = feat_accuracy_df['TestAccuracy'].astype(float)
    #race_accuracy_df
    
    X_axis = np.arange(len(feat_accuracy_df[feature]))
    plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (20,10)
    bar1 = plt.bar(X_axis, (feat_accuracy_df['TrainAccuracy']), width=0.50, color='b', align='center')
    bar2 = plt.bar(X_axis+0.4, (feat_accuracy_df['TestAccuracy']), width=0.50, color='g', align='center')

    plt.xticks(X_axis, feat_accuracy_df[feature])
    plt.xlabel(feature)
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.title("{featName} Vs Accuracy on Random Forest".format(featName=feature))
    plt.legend( (bar1, bar2), ('Training Accuracy', 'Test Accuracy') )
    
    if len(feat_accuracy_df[feature]) >= 10:
        plt.xticks(rotation=90)

    plt.show()

Declare our K-NN classifier function. It also has the capability of classifying using Epsilon ball NN.

In [48]:
def dist(x, y):
    return np.sqrt(np.dot(x-y,(x-y).T))

def knn_classify(k, train_x, train_y, X, epsilon):
    distances = []
    for i in range(0, len(train_x)):
        distances.append((dist(X, train_x[i]), train_y[i]))
    distances.sort()
    count = 0
    if epsilon:
        ptr = 0
        while ptr < len(distances) and distances[ptr][0] < k:
            if distances[ptr][1] == 1:
                count += 1
            else:
                count -= 1
            ptr += 1
        if ptr == 0:
            count = distances[0][1]
    else:
        for i in range(0, k):
            if distances[i][1] == 1:
                count += 1
            else:
                count -= 1
    return 1 if count >= 0 else -1

Now, let's try running the K-NN classifier on our dataset for different values of K and compare how it affects the accuracy of the model.

In [49]:

count = 0
correct_frac = []
for n in neighbor_nums:
    preds = []
    for vec in knn_test_x:
        count += 1
        preds.append(knn_classify(n, knn_train_x, knn_train_y, vec, False))
    num_correct = sum(x == y for x,y in zip(knn_test_y, preds)) / len(knn_test_y)
    correct_frac.append(num_correct)

Perceptron Classifier¶

Declare perceptron class

In [53]:
class Perceptron():
    def __init__(self):
        self.weights = 0
        self.bias = 0
        self.updates = 0
    
    def predict(self, X):
        if self.updates == 0:
            return 0
        else:
            return np.dot(self.weights, X) + self.bias
        
    def train_example(self, X, Y):
        if Y * self.predict(X) <= 0:
            self.updates += 1
            self.weights = self.weights + (Y * X)
            self.bias = self.bias + Y

Make new train/test set

Combining similar data values¶

We see that there are many possible values for highest education among all of the induviduals in the sample. We will combine values that mean essentially the same thing since the abundence of values could effectively confuse our models, resulting in less accuracy. We will bucket "9th", "10th","11th" "12th", into "HS-no-grad", "5th-6th" and "7th-8th" into "Middle-school", "1st-4th" into "Elementary_school", "Prof-school" into "Doctorate", and finally "Assoc-acdm" and "Assoc-voc" into "Assoc".

Reducing skew in the data¶

Before training any models on the dataset, we reduce the skew of certain variables that have a significant amount of skew. This will allow our classification models to learn more effectively.

Let's see how skewed the data is before we take any further action:

We can see that capital gain and capital loss appear to have the most right skew out of any variables. Capital gain is also a highly correlated variable, it is important to reduce this skew so that our models are able to learn the data more easily and accurately. We will do so by using a cube root transformation. Capital gain will be reduced by exponentiating by the cube root twice, and capital loss will be reduced by exponentiating by the cube root once.

In [79]:
data['capital_gain'] = (data['capital_gain'] ** (1/3)) ** (1/3)
data['capital_loss'] = data['capital_loss'] ** (1/3)

We can now observe a significant reduction in the skew of the afformentioned variables.

Tuning Hyperparameters¶

The gradient boosting model allows us to tune parameters of 3 different categories. They are as follows:

  • Tree specific parameters: modify induvidual trees generated in the model
  • Boosting parameters: modify the boosting operations within the model
  • Miscellaneous: modify the general function of the model, like the loss function

We will start by initializing some start values. They will be:

  • min_samples_split: set equal to ~1% of total data points (490)
  • min_samples_leaf: set to 50
  • max_depth: set to 6
  • max_features: set to 'sqrt'
  • subsample: set to 0.8

Now we can start by determining an optimal number of estimators for the model. This value "n_estimators" dictates how many sequential trees will be modeled.

In [84]:
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size = 0.2)

test_est = {'n_estimators':range(220,501,10)}
gs = GridSearchCV(estimator = GradientBoostingClassifier(learning_rate=0.1, min_samples_split=490,min_samples_leaf=50,max_depth=6,max_features='sqrt',subsample=0.8,random_state=20), 
param_grid = test_est, scoring='roc_auc',n_jobs=4, cv=5)
gs.fit(x_train, y_train)

gs.best_params_, gs.best_score_

({'n_estimators': 340}, 0.9268035216965409)

We find that "n_estimators" = 320 is optimal.

We continue to tune the most important parameters of the model, "max_depth" and "min_samples_split". We also add "n_estimators" = 320 to our model.

Plotting accuracy of Features with Low Diversity Individually¶

In [148]:
def plotAccuracyforFeature(feature, model):
    feature_dfs = {}
    for feat in original_data[feature].unique():
        feature_dfs[feat] = (original_data.loc[original_data[feature] == feat])
        
    for feat in feature_dfs.keys():
        feature_dfs[feat]['workclass'] = le.fit_transform(feature_dfs[feat]['workclass'])
        feature_dfs[feat]['highest_education'] = le.fit_transform(feature_dfs[feat]['highest_education'])
        feature_dfs[feat]['marital_status'] = le.fit_transform(feature_dfs[feat]['marital_status'])
        feature_dfs[feat]['occupation'] = le.fit_transform(feature_dfs[feat]['occupation'])
        feature_dfs[feat]['relationship'] = le.fit_transform(feature_dfs[feat]['relationship'])
        feature_dfs[feat]['sex'] = le.fit_transform(feature_dfs[feat]['sex'])
        feature_dfs[feat]['race'] = le.fit_transform(feature_dfs[feat]['race'])
        feature_dfs[feat]['native_country'] = le.fit_transform(feature_dfs[feat]['native_country'])
        
        feature_dfs[feat] = feature_dfs[feat].drop(feature, axis=1)
     
    
    accuracy = {}
    for feat in feature_dfs.keys():
        sc = StandardScaler()
        data_x = feature_dfs[feat].drop('salary', axis = 'columns')
        
        y = feature_dfs[feat]['salary']

        scaled_data_x = sc.fit_transform(data_x)
        x = pd.DataFrame(scaled_data_x, columns = data_x.columns)

        
        if x.shape[0] == 1:
            X_train = X_test = x
            y_train = y_test = y
        else:
            X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size=0.20, random_state=20)

        gb = GradientBoostingClassifier(learning_rate=0.1, n_estimators=320, min_samples_split=600,min_samples_leaf=40,max_depth=7,max_features='sqrt',subsample=0.8,random_state=20)
        gb = gb.fit(X_train, y_train)
        
        train_pred = gb.predict(X_train)
        test_pred = gb.predict(X_test)
        test_acc = accuracy_score(y_test, test_pred)
        train_acc = accuracy_score(y_train, train_pred)

        accuracy[feat] = {'trainAcc': float(train_acc), 'testAcc': float(test_acc)}
        
    
    feat_accuracy_df = []
    for key in accuracy.keys():
        tmp = [key, accuracy[key]['trainAcc'],accuracy[key]['testAcc']]
        feat_accuracy_df.append(tmp)

    feat_accuracy_df = np.array(feat_accuracy_df)
    feat_accuracy_df = pd.DataFrame(feat_accuracy_df, columns=[feature,'TrainAccuracy','TestAccuracy'])
    feat_accuracy_df['TrainAccuracy'] = feat_accuracy_df['TrainAccuracy'].astype(float)
    feat_accuracy_df['TestAccuracy'] = feat_accuracy_df['TestAccuracy'].astype(float)
    #race_accuracy_df
    
    X_axis = np.arange(len(feat_accuracy_df[feature]))
    plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (20,10)
    bar1 = plt.bar(X_axis, (feat_accuracy_df['TrainAccuracy']), width=0.50, color='b', align='center')
    bar2 = plt.bar(X_axis+0.4, (feat_accuracy_df['TestAccuracy']), width=0.50, color='g', align='center')

    plt.xticks(X_axis, feat_accuracy_df[feature])
    plt.xlabel(feature)
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.title("{featName} Vs Accuracy on {modelName}".format(featName=feature, modelName=model))
    plt.legend( (bar1, bar2), ('Training Accuracy', 'Test Accuracy') )
    
    if len(feat_accuracy_df[feature]) >= 10:
        plt.xticks(rotation=90)

    plt.show()
